description: Dave Asprey Convincing evidence that waking up before dawn can increase your chances of getting cancer.  Just like staying up late. When you wake up before sunrise and flick on the lights, or stay up past sunrise under bright lights, you break that system over time.  We are facing an epidemic we didn't plan for because LED indoor lights have FIVE TIMES more of the type of light that confuses your brain's timing system compared to incandascent bulbs. A better word to describe our ability to regain partial function is to “reclaim.” Reclaiming means to retrieve or recover something that has previously been lost.   With SCI, unfortunately, mainstream thinking considers “walking again” as the Holy Grail. But reclaiming goes well beyond walking. In fact, walking is a small part of living, and it is possible to reclaim all or nearly all of the best that life has to offer — love, companionship, happiness, fulfillment, a sense of purpose, belonging to a community, faith, hope, gratitude, compassion for others, dedication to a cause or passion — without ever standing or taking another step."

description: Maciej Aleks Cybulski  posted a  video  from August 27, 2014 to his Timeline —  feeling thankful at  Havasupai Falls in Supai, Arizona (Supai Indian Reservation) . Sorry for all the worrying!!!! I'm HOME & SAFE!!! The plan was always to come home Thursday. There was NO uncertainty, my itinerary was very clear, I had called my dad Monday to let him know that I would have ZERO cell phone reception until late Thursday once we hit Route 66 and 40. I clearly stated that if we don't make it home by Friday, send out the brigade, but the goal was to be home by Thursday dinner time. (I don't know who said lunch time as it took me over 7 hours to climb out of the canyon - a mere 10 mile hike, with a backpack and in the heat of the day - my lunch was trail mix and a mozzarella stick!) It was a HUGE challenge physically and mentally. It was very awkward not having my cell phone available for texting and calling, but at the same time my dad knew we'd return Thursday. We left the hilltop by car around 6pm, so a decent 4 hour drive should have been a reachable goal; but I got a flat tire on the Indian Road 18 where of course there was NO CELL RECEPTION. We finally got home at 1:45am because I had to drive slower than my usual slow driving since I had a spare donut on my car that recommends not going above 50 mph. It was a 4 day adventure that I cannot even begin to describe. An absolutely amazing expedition that challenged me on so many levels; it could almost be described as life changing!
